2 HOUSE BILL 1164
1 Annotated Code of Maryland
2 (2025 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
3 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
4 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
5 Article – Public Utilities
6 1–101.
7 (a) In this division the following words have the meanings indicated.
8 (z) (1) “Public service company” means a common carrier company, electric
9 company, gas company, sewage disposal company, telegraph company, telephone company,
10 water company, or any combination of public service companies.
11 (2) “Public service company” does not include:
12 (i) a campground that provides water, electric, gas, sewage, or
13 telephone service to campers incident to the campground’s primary business of operating
14 and maintaining the campground; or
15 (ii) a person that owns or operates equipment used for charging
16 electric vehicles, including a person that owns or operates:
17 1. an electric vehicle charging station;
18 2. electric vehicle supply equipment; or
19 3. an electric vehicle charging station service company or
20 provider.
21 (gg) “Sewage disposal company” means a privately owned public service company
22 that owns or maintains facilities for the disposal of sewage.
23 (uu) “Water company” means a public service company that owns a water plant
24 and sells or distributes water for gain.
25 4–307.
26 (a) (1) In this section[, rate] THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
27 INDICATED.
28 (2) “RATE consolidation” means the use of the same or similar rates or
29 tariff schedules of rates for customers of the same class for two or more water or sewage
30 disposal systems even if the systems are not physically interconnected.

HOUSE BILL 1164 3
1 (3) “RATES” INCLUDES FIXED RATES, VOLUMETRIC RATES, TOLLS,
2 CHARGES, AND SCHEDULES.
3 (4) “SYSTEM” MEANS AN INTERCONNECTED SYSTEM OF FACILITIES
4 USED BY A WATER COMPANY, SEWAGE DISPOSAL COMPANY, OR WATER AND SEWAGE
5 DISPOSAL COMPANY TO PROVIDE WATER OR SEWAGE DISPOSAL SERVICES.
6 [(b) After notice to customers and holding a public hearing and an evidentiary
7 hearing, the Commission may authorize a rate consolidation of two or more water or sewage
8 disposal systems if:
9 (1) the water or sewage disposal systems have common ownership; and
10 (2) the rate consolidation is in the public interest.]
11 (B) THIS SECTION APPLIES ONLY TO PUBLIC SERVICE COMPANIES THAT
12 ARE WATER COMPANIES, SEWAGE DISPOSAL COMPANIES, OR WATER AND SEWAGE
13 DISPOSAL COMPANIES.
14 (C) THE COMMISSION SHALL AUTHORIZE A RATE CONSOLIDATION
15 PROPOSED BY A PUBLIC SERVICE COMPANY IN A BASE RATE PROCEEDING UNDER §
16 4–203 OF THIS TITLE INVOLVING TWO OR MORE WATER SYSTEMS OR SEWAGE
17 DISPOSAL SYSTEMS.
18 (D) WHEN AUTHORIZING RATE CONSOLIDATION UNDER SUBSECTION (C) OF
19 THIS SECTION, THE COMMISSION:
20 (1) SHALL ALLOW THE PUBLIC SERVICE COMPANY TO AGGREGATE
21 THE REVENUES AND COSTS OF THE WATER SYSTEMS AND SEWAGE DISPOSAL
22 SYSTEMS FOR PURPOSES OF DETERMINING APPROPRIATE RATES FOR THE SYSTEMS’
23 CUSTOMERS; AND
24 (2) MAY ORDER GRADUAL ADJUSTMENTS TO THE RATES CHARGED TO
25 A SYSTEM OVER A PERIOD NOT TO EXCEED 3 YEARS UNTIL FULL RATE
26 CONSOLIDATION IS ACHIEVED.
27 (E) THE COMMISSION:
28 (1) MAY NOT DISAPPROVE A RATE CONSOLIDATION PROPOSAL UNDER
29 THIS SECTION; AND
30 (2) MAY CONDITION THE AUTHORIZATION OF A RATE CONSOLIDATION
31 PROPOSAL ONLY AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (D)(2) OF THIS SECTION.

4 HOUSE BILL 1164
1 (F) AFTER THE COMMISSION HAS AUTHORIZED A RATE CONSOLIDATION
2 PROPOSAL UNDER THIS SECTION, THE COMMISSION SHALL CONTINUE TO
3 AUTHORIZE AND MAINTAIN THE RATE CONSOLIDATION IN SUBSEQUENT ORDERS ON
4 APPLICATIONS OF THE PUBLIC SERVICE COMPANY UNDER § 4–203 OF THIS TITLE.
5 4–309.
6 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
7 (2) “Eligible limited–income customer” means a residential customer of a
8 utility company with annual income that:
9 (i) 1. is at or below 175% of the federal poverty level; or
10 2. for a customer at least 67 years of age, is at or below 200%
11 of the federal poverty level; or
12 (ii) meets a broader designation approved by the Commission.
13 (3) “Limited–income mechanism” or “mechanism” means a process
14 approved by the Commission under this section to benefit an eligible limited–income
15 customer of a utility company.
16 (4) “Payment plan” means an agreement between an eligible
17 limited–income customer and a utility company to pay an arrearage balance over a specific
18 period of time to avoid disconnection of a utility service.
19 (5) (i) “Utility company” means:
20 1. an electric company[,];
21 2. a gas and electric company[, or];
22 3. a gas company;
23 4. A WATER COMPANY;
24 5. A WATER AND SEWAGE DISPOSAL COMPANY; OR
25 6. A SEWAGE DISPOSAL COMPANY.
26 (ii) “Utility company” does not include a small rural electric
27 cooperative.

HOUSE BILL 1164 5
1 (b) The General Assembly finds and declares that the societal benefits of a
2 well–constructed limited–income mechanism to benefit Maryland’s eligible limited–income
3 customers are in the public interest.
4 (c) (1) Subject to the approval of the Commission, a utility company shall
5 adopt a limited–income mechanism to benefit an eligible limited–income customer.
6 (2) Notwithstanding § 4–503(b) of this title, the mechanism may take the
7 form of a program, tariff provision, credit, rate, rider, or other means to assist an eligible
8 limited–income customer to afford a utility service.
9 (3) A municipal electric utility may adopt a limited–income mechanism
10 subject to the approval of the Commission in the same manner as a utility company in
11 accordance with this section.
12 (d) (1) A utility company that proposes a limited–income mechanism for
13 Commission approval under subsection (c) of this section shall include the proposal in:
14 (i) a separate application for approval of the mechanism; or
15 (ii) only with the prior approval of the Commission, an application
16 for a base rate proceeding, including an alternative rate proceeding, or any other proceeding
17 to alter the utility company’s base rates under the authority of the Commission.
18 (2) A proposal submitted under this section shall allocate the prudently
19 incurred costs of the limited–income mechanism across rate classes.
20 (3) The proposal shall include:
21 (i) a detailed description of the proposed mechanism;
22 (ii) the proposed method for allocating the mechanism’s costs across
23 customer classes;
24 (iii) the rationale supporting the utility company’s proposal for a
25 mechanism to benefit the eligible limited–income customers in the utility company’s service
26 territory;
27 (iv) a time frame and process for the Commission to review the
28 effectiveness of the mechanism after implementation; and
29 (v) any other information the Commission considers necessary or
30 useful to evaluate the proposal.
31 (e) In evaluating a limited–income mechanism, the Commission shall consider:

6 HOUSE BILL 1164
1 (1) the degree to which the mechanism promotes affordability of WATER,
2 SEWAGE DISPOSAL, electricity, or natural gas for limited–income customers;
3 (2) the public interest in allocating the costs of the mechanism between the
4 utility company’s shareholders and rate payers;
5 (3) the impact on rates, utility operating costs, customer arrearages,
6 customer disconnections, uncollectible costs, and successful completion of payment plans;
7 (4) the ability of a limited–income customer to continue to receive benefits
8 when relocating within the same service territory;
9 (5) coordination of benefits under the mechanism with any other public or
10 private assistance that may be available to the customer;
11 (6) a minimum level of support or assistance structure to provide equitable
12 availability of limited–income assistance across the State; and
13 (7) any other information the Commission considers appropriate.
14 (f) If an approved limited–income mechanism requires that the Office of Home
15 Energy Programs must certify an eligible limited–income customer’s qualifications to
16 participate in a limited–income mechanism, the Office shall certify an eligible
17 limited–income customer’s qualifications before the customer may participate in the
18 mechanism.
19 (g) An eligible limited–income customer who participates in a mechanism under
20 this section may also be eligible for other assistance programs offered in the State,
21 including those offered by a utility company or the Office of Home Energy Programs, the
22 Department of Housing and Community Development, or any other public or private
23 source.
24 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
25 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
26 (2) “Eligible limited–income customer” and “limited–income mechanism”
27 have the meanings stated in § 4–309 of the Public Utilities Article.
28 (3) “Sewage disposal company” and “water company” have the meanings
29 stated in § 1–101 of the Public Utilities Article.
30 (b) The Public Service Commission shall study the feasibility of requiring the
31 following companies to adopt a limited–income mechanism to benefit eligible
32 limited–income customers:
33 (1) a water company;

HOUSE BILL 1164 7
1 (2) a water and sewage disposal company; and
2 (3) a sewage disposal company.
3 (c) On or before December 1, 2026, the Public Service Commission shall report its
4 findings to the Governor and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article,
5 the General Assembly.
6 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That Section 1 of this Act shall take
7 effect July 1, 2027.
8 SECTION 2. 4. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, except as provided in
9 Section 3 of this Act, this Act shall take effect July 1, 2026.
Approved:
